04501nam a22007095i 9781501757013DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20212017nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017570137 a10.1515/97815017570132doi  a(DE-B1597)572254  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aDK49b.G55 2017 7aHIS0320002bisacsh04a303.48/24705090422231 aGlebov, Sergey, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFrom Empire to Eurasia :bPolitics, Scholarship, and Ideology in Russian Eurasianism, 1920s–1930s /cSergey Glebov. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2021] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (238 p.) :b2 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNIU Series in Slavic, East European, and Eurasian Studies00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tINTRODUCTION. Eurasia’s Many Meanings -- tCHAPTER 1: EXILES FROM THE SILVER AGE -- tCHAPTER 2: THE MONGOL– BOLSHEVIK REVOLUTION -- tCHAPTER 3: THE ANTICOLONIALIST EMPIRE -- tCHAPTER 4: IN SEARCH OF WHOLENESS -- tCHAPTER 5: THE STRUCTURES OF EURASIA -- tEPILOGUE. Eurasianism as a Movement -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Eurasianist movement was launched in the 1920s by a group of young Russian émigrés who had recently emerged from years of fighting and destruction. Drawing on the cultural fermentation of Russian modernism in the arts and literature, as well as in politics and scholarship, the movement sought to reimagine the former imperial space in the wake of Europe's Great War. The Eurasianists argued that as an heir to the nomadic empires of the steppes, Russia should follow a non-European path of development. In the context of rising Nazi and Soviet powers, the Eurasianists rejected liberal democracy and sought alternatives to Communism and capitalism. Deeply connected to the Russian cultural and scholarly milieus, Eurasianism played a role in the articulation of the structuralist paradigm in interwar Europe. However, the movement was not as homogenous as its name may suggest. Its founders disagreed on a range of issues and argued bitterly about what weight should be accorded to one or another idea in their overall conception of Eurasia. In this first English language history of the Eurasianist movement based on extensive archival research, Sergey Glebov offers a historically grounded critique of the concept of Eurasia by interrogating the context in which it was first used to describe the former Russian Empire. This definitive study will appeal to students and scholars of Russian and European history and culture.    aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aEurasian schoolxHistoryy20th century. 0aIdeologyzSoviet UnionxHistory. 0aLearning and scholarshipxPolitical aspectszSoviet UnionxHistory. 4aHistory. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 4aSoviet & East European History. 7aHISTORY / Russia & the Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311066587140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150175701340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501757013423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501757013/original  a978-3-11-066587-1  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK